<chapter xml:id="chapter-1">
  <title>Basic geometry in <m>\mathbb{N}_0 \times \mathbb{N}_0</m></title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter we first give a detailed description of the geometry of the support of polynomials
      in <m>K[x,y]</m> and the relation with the plane Jacobian conjecture. 
      Then we introduce our main tools: directions and leading terms <m>\ell_{\rho\sigma}(P)</m> 
      corresponding to these directions (see <xref ref="defino1_1"/>), 
      the transformation of the shape of the support by certain automorphisms of <m>K[x,y]</m>, and the very important element <m>F</m>. 
      The main result of this chapter is that if the Jacobian conjecture is false, then <m>B \ge 9</m>, 
      where <m>B := \min\bigl(\gcd(\deg(P),\deg(Q))\bigr)</m>, and <m>(P,Q)</m> runs on the counterexamples. 
      This result was already proven by Nagata in <cite>Nagata</cite>. In order to prove <m>B \ge 9</m>, we consider
      a counterexample <m>(P,Q)</m> such that <m>B = \gcd(\deg(P),\deg(Q))</m>. We transform this counterexample into 
      a standard <m>(m,n)</m>-pair in <m>K[x,y]</m> (see <xref ref="defino1_2"/>). For the transformed pair there exist 
      <m>(\rho,\sigma)</m>-homogeneous elements (see <xref ref="defino1_3"/>) <m>R</m> and <m>F</m> 
      satisfying very strong conditions (see <xref ref="defino1_4"/>). The supports of <m>R</m> and <m>F</m> 
      satisfying these conditions, with minimum <m>\deg(R)</m>, are shown in <xref ref="img1-1"/>.
    </p> 
      <figure xml:id="img1-1">
        <image width="30%" source="img/img1.png"/>
        <caption>Minimal possible support of F and R</caption>
      </figure>

    <p><m>\deg(R) = 9</m>, which implies <m>B \geq 9</m>. The key point of the proof is the transformation of the minimal 
      counterexample into a standard <m>(m,n)</m>-pair, which needs the most amount of work. This transformation is carried 
      out using automorphisms of the algebra <m>K[x,y]</m>, which alter the support of the polynomials—subsets 
      of <m>\mathbb{N}_0 \times \mathbb{N}_0</m>—through basic geometric operations on the plane.
      The shaping of the support depends on the multiplicity of the linear factors in the polynomials <m>\ell_{\rho\sigma}(P)</m>, 
      which are strongly conditioned by the multiplicity of these linear factors in the <m>(\rho,\sigma)</m>-homogeneous polynomial 
      <m>F</m> (see <xref ref="defino1_5"/>).
      This underlines the importance of the element <m>F</m>, which is the crucial new tool of our whole approach.
    </p>
 </introduction>

  <!-- ===================== -->
  <!-- SECTION 1.1 -->     \operatorname{Supp}(P) := \{(i,j) : a_{ij} \neq 0\}
  <!-- ===================== -->

  <section xml:id="sec-1-1">
    <title>Polynomials in two variables and their support</title>
    <p>Polynomials in two variables over a field <m>K</m> are expressions of the form</p>
    <me>
      P(x,y) = \sum_{i,j \in \mathbb{N}_0} a_{ij} x^i y^j
    </me>
    <p>For example:</p>
    <me>
      P = 3x^3 + 2x^2 + 4xy + 7y^2 + 2y - 8
    </me>
    <p> The <term>support</term> of a polynomial is defined as: </p>

    <me>
      \operatorname{Supp} (P) := \{(i,j) : a_{ij} \neq 0\}
    </me>

    <figure xml:id="img1-2">
      <image width="30%" source="img/img2.png"/>   //width="400px"   height="300px"
      <caption>Support of P</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The algebra <m>K[x,y]</m> has basis 
      <m>\{x^i y^j : (i,j) \in \mathbb{N}_0^2\}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      x^i y^j \cdot x^k y^l = x^{i+k} y^{j+l}
    </me>
    <p>
      on elements of the basis, and then extended by bilinearity to arbitrary polynomials. If one of <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> is a monomial, then the support of the product is the sum of the supports. Here we define the <term>sum</term> and the <term>difference</term> of two subsets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, by
    </p>

    <me>
      A + B := \{a + b : a \in A \text{ and } b \in B\}
      \quad \text{and} \quad
      A - B := \{a - b : a \in A \text{ and } b \in B\},
    </me>

    <p>
      respectively. For example, if
    </p>

    <me>
      P = 3x^3 + 2x^2 + 4xy + 7y^2 + 2y - 8
      \quad \text{and} \quad
      Q = x^3 y,
    </me>

  </section>




